The '''Southern Buh''', '''Bug''', or '''Boh''' River ({{lang-uk|<U+041F><U+0456><U+0432><U+0434><U+0435><U+043D><U+043D><U+0438><U+0439> <U+0411><U+0443><U+0433>}}, ''Pivdennyi Buh''; {{lang-pl|Boh}}; {{lang-ru|<U+042E><U+0436><U+043D><U+044B><U+0439> <U+0411><U+0443><U+0433>}}, ''Yuzhny Bug'', [[ancient Greek]]: Hypanis, Ottoman {{lang-tr|Aksu}}),  is entirely located in [[Ukraine]].  It rises in the west, in the [[Podolia]]n uplands, about 145&nbsp;km from the Polish border, and flows southeasterly into the [[Black Sea]] through the southern steppe. It is 806&nbsp;km long and drains 63,700&nbsp;km<U+00B2>.

Its name may be related to the [[proto-Germanic]] "Bug" which is translated as "bow", the name having been given by [[Goths]], who arrived here in 2-3 centuries AD. During the [[Migrations Period]] the river Bug was an important obstacle to all the migrating tribes, who often were held up in what later became the city of [[Chi<U+015F>in<U+0103>u]]. This is why the name of Chishineu originally translates as "The camp". 
Other major cities on the Southern Bug: [[Khmelnytskyi, Ukraine|Khmelnytskyi]], [[Vinnytsia]], [[Pervomaisk, Mykolaiv Oblast|Pervomaisk]], [[Mykolaiv]].

